hat kind of a feminist anthropology is needed in such a moment? The Twilight of Cutting examines these and other questions from the vantage point of Ghanaian feminist and reproductive health NGOs that have organized campaigns against cutting for over thirty years. The book looks at these NGOs not as solutions but as sites of “problematization.” The purpose of understanding these Ghanaian campaigns, their transnational and regional encounters, and the forms of governmentality they produce is not to charge them with providing answers to the question, how do we end cutting? Instead, it is to account for their work, their historicity, the life worlds and subjectivities they engender, and the modes of reflection, imminent critique, and opposition they set in motion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemale circumcisionxPolitical aspectsxGhana. 0aFemale circumcisionxPolitical aspectszGhana. 0aFemale circumcisionxPreventionxGhana. 0aFemale circumcisionzGhanaxPrevention. 0aFemale genital mutilationxPolitical aspectszGhana. 0aFemale genital mutilationzGhanaxPrevention. 0aFeminismxGhanaxGhana. 0aFeminismzGhana. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxSocial aspectsxGhana. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxSocial aspectszGhana. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965577?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965577/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles